        "body": "Fixes #16072.\r\n\r\nThis PR fixes an issue where Mongoose’s strict-mode path validation would silently remove `$set` update paths in `findByIdAndUpdate` when using `arrayFilters` if the update path crossed a discriminator boundary and targeted a deeply nested field, such as a key inside a Map.\r\n\r\n### Root Cause\r\n\r\nThe problem came from `lib/helpers/query/getEmbeddedDiscriminatorPath.js`. After detecting the correct discriminator schema, the code used the `path()` method to resolve the remaining subpath.\r\n\r\nHowever, `path()` only performs top-level schema lookups and cannot properly resolve deeply nested paths or dynamic Map keys. Because of this limitation, update paths like:\r\n\r\nevents.$[event].products.map.key\r\n\r\ncould not be resolved through the discriminator schema. As a result, Mongoose’s strict-mode validation would silently strip the path from the `$set` update.\r\n\r\nSince the update path was removed, MongoDB received the `arrayFilters` but no update referencing them, which caused MongoDB to throw the error:\r\n\r\nMongoServerError: The array filter for identifier 'event' was not used in the update\r\n\r\n### Fix\r\n\r\nThis PR replaces the use of `path()` with `_getSchema()`, which correctly traverses nested sub-schemas and Map structures.\r\n\r\nWith this change, Mongoose is able to properly resolve deeply nested paths inside discriminator schemas, so the update path is preserved and sent to MongoDB as expected.\r\n\r\n### Tests\r\n\r\nA new test has been added in:\r\n\r\ntest/model.discriminator.querying.test.js\r\n\r\nThis test reproduces the issue where an update targeting:\r\n\r\nevents.$[event].products.map.key\r\n\r\nwould previously be stripped during strict validation when used with discriminated subdocuments and `arrayFilters`.\r\n\r\nWith the fix applied, the path is now correctly preserved and the update executes successfully.",
